gion rich with social and political mobilizations. This fully revised second edition extends the earlier explorations of Egypt, Morocco, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia, and Turkey, and adds new case studies on the uprisings in Tunisia, Syria, and Yemen. The case studies are inspired by social movement theory, but they also critique and expand the horizons of the theory's classical concepts of political opportunity structures, collective action frames, mobilization structures, and repertoires of contention based on intensive fieldwork. This strong empirical base allows for a nuanced understanding of contexts, culturally conditioned rationality, the strengths and weaknesses of local networks, and innovation in contentious action to give the reader a substantive understanding of events in the Arab world before and since 2011.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aPolitical participationzAfrica, NorthvCase studies. 0aPolitical participationzMiddle EastvCase studies. 0aSocial movementsxPolitical aspectszAfrica, NorthvCase studies. 0aSocial movementsxPolitical aspectszMiddle EastvCase studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aBeinin, Joel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVairel, Frédéric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478803840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804788038423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804788038.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles